<H1><a name="welcome">Welcome!</A></H1>

<P>
The <I><B>Journal of Online Law</B></I> (&quot;<I><B>JOL</B></I>&quot;)
has been in the planning for quite a few months now; it is a real
pleasure to bring it to the light of day. I am more grateful than
I know how to say to the authors-Michael Froomkin, Ethan Katsh,
Mark Lemley, and David Post-who have written superbly thoughtful
essays for this premier release. Writing for a new journal is
a little like jumping from an airplane with an untested parachute:
you certainly hope it will be successful, but it's a bit of a
gamble. I am exceedingly happy that these folks took the gamble;
for me, the success of the venture is readily apparent, but it's
really up to you, the readers, to make that decision for yourselves.
(Though I hope you'll agree with me!)
<P>
I'd also like to thank those folks, listed under <a href="#advboard">Advisory Board</A>,
who agreed to serve on the <I><B>JOL</B></I> Advisory Board. They've
been kind enough to offer suggestions, respond to ideas, and give
general moral support (and in some cases, also serve as authors).
<P>
Finally, and once again, I am extremely grateful to the four authors
who have written for this first release. I hope that readers will
enjoy their work!
<H2>Preview of the next release </H2>

<P>
We are currently planning for an upcoming release of <I><B>JOL</B></I>
in the fall to focus on &quot;commerce on the net.&quot; We'll
be looking at things like the economic effects of digital cash
and the likelihood that governments will permit anonymous financial
transactions over the net. If you have an interest in submitting
an article on that (or another topic), please drop a note to <a href="mailto:Editor@JOL.law.wm.edu">Editor@jol.law.wm.edu</A>.
Thanks. Submissions will be peer reviewed.
<H2>Hope you'll give us feedback</H2>

<P>
If you like this release of <I><B>JOL</B></I>, or don't like it,
or have something to say about it, please drop us a note at the
above e-mail address. Some letters may get printed in the next
release, or posted on our Web page, so when you write, please
do so with that understanding.
<P>
Thanks for your interest in-and welcome to-the <I><B>Journal of
Online Law</B></I>!
<P>
<I><a href="mailto:thardy@facstaff.wm.edu">Trotter Hardy</A><BR>
</I>Editor<HR>

<H1><a name="what">What is the Journal of Online Law?</A></H1>

<P>
<I><B>The Journal of Online Law</B></I> (&quot;<I><B>JOL</B></I>&quot;)
is an electronic publication of scholarly essays about law and
online communications-law and cyberspace. The first issue was
released early in June, 1995.
<P>
&quot;Scholarly essays&quot; means thoughtful, readable pieces
that analyze current trends in the law and predict future disputes
and problems. A journal of scholarly essays is different from
the typical &quot;law review&quot; or &quot;law journal.&quot;
The latter emphasizes comprehensiveness, thoroughness, and reliance
on detailed footnotes. These characteristics have their place;
we simply intend something different: a journal that is shorter,
more easily readable, having wider appeal.
<P>
Nor is <I><B>JOL</B></I> is the place for detailed review of particular
court decisions, or for advice on specific situations. Countless
publications like newsletters, law firm practice updates, and
law reviews provide outlets for those different and worthy endeavors.
<P>
The <I><B>Journal of Online Law</B></I> is rather aimed at concisely
framing and exploring the key legal issues arising from networked
communication; at speculating a bit about future trends; and in
general, at trying to bring interested readers some interesting
reading about the law of cyberspace.
<P>
Electronic distribution is a &quot;natural&quot; for a journal
that deals with cyberspace. Nonetheless, our first priority is
not the medium but the message: we care most of all interesting,
intelligent, and readable content. If you do too, then we think
you will receiving <I><B>The Journal of Online Law</B></I>.<HR>

<H1>Masthead </H1>

<H3><a name="editor">Editor:</A></H3>

<UL>
<LI><B><a href="mailto:thardy@facstaff.wm.edu">Trotter Hardy</A></B>, the 
William and Mary School of Law </UL>

<H3><a name="advboard">Advisory Board:</A></H3>

<UL>
<LI><B>Thomas R. Bruce</B>, Co-Director, Legal Information Institute
Research Associate, Cornell Law School
<LI><B>David R. Johnson</B>, Chairman, Lexis Counsel Connect;
Chairman, Electronic Frontier Foundation
