<BR>
<H1>WHAT IS INFO SOURCE?</H1><P>This document is organized as
follows:</P>             <UL>
<LI><STRONG>Introduction to Info Source</STRONG></LI>
<LI><STRONG><a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/ise0001.html#introaccess">Introduction to the Access to Information Act</A></STRONG></LI>
<LI><STRONG><a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/ise0001.html#introprivacy">Introdu
ction to the Privacy Act</A></STRONG></LI>
<LI><STRONG><a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/ise0001.html#requesting">Requesting 
Information under the Acts</A></STRONG></LI></UL><H2>1.
Introduction to Info Source</H2>
<P><STRONG>Info Source</STRONG> is the federal government's
step-by-step guide that makes it easy to find out about the Government
of Canada, its organization, and its information holdings. It is
available in either print publications or a computer database. Both the
publications and the database are available in English and French.</P>
<P><STRONG>Info Source</STRONG> is the key to learning how to exercise
your rights under two Canadian laws -- the <I>Access to Information Act</I>
and the <I>Privacy Act.</I></P>
<P><STRONG>Info Source</STRONG> makes it easy to locate program
records and personal information by providing succinct and easy-to-read
descriptions of these records. It is also designed to assist you in
finding the departments, organizational units and phone numbers of
people who can help.</P>
<P>The <STRONG>Info Source</STRONG> online service has two main
components, as follows:</P>
<P><EM>(a)  General Information
</EM></P><UL>
<LI><a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/ise0001.html">Background
information on the project</A></LI>
<LI><a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/isez001.html">Addresses
and phone numbers of Access to Information and Privacy coordinators.</A>
The coordinator's staff can answer your questions and help identify the
records you wish to see.
</LI>
<LI><a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/ise0002.html">News
and Announcements</A></LI></UL><DL>
<DT><EM>(b)  Searchable Databases</EM></DT>
<DD>(i)   <STRONG><a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/ise2001.html"> Sources of Federal
Government Information</A></STRONG><DL>
<DD> This database contains entries for each department and agency
covered by the <I>Access to Information Act</I> and the <I>Privacy Act</I>.
Each entry provides information on the institution's
background, responsibilities, legislation, organization and information
holdings (program records and  personal information banks).</DD></DL></DD>
<DD>(ii)  <STRONG><a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/iee2001.html"> Sources of Federal
Employee Information</A></STRONG><DL>
<DD>This database contains descriptions of the records held by the
federal government on its employees.</DD>
</DL></DD>
<DD>(iii) <STRONG><a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/ise2001.html">Guide to Sources of
Federal Government Information</A></STRONG><DL>
<DD>This database provides telephone numbers, addresses and general fax
numbers for the national offices of more than 250 federal
institutions.</DD></DL></DD>
</DL>
<H3>Where to obtain Info Source</H3><P>For information on subscribing
to the <STRONG>Info Source</STRONG> databases, or if you would like to
purchase a copy of an <STRONG>Info Source</STRONG> publication, please
contact:</P><PRE><STRONG><a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/">QL Systems Limited</A>
Toll Free:     1-800-387-0899
Telephone:     (613) 238-3499 (Ottawa area)
Fax:           (613) 238-7597</STRONG></PRE><H2><a name="introaccess">2.
Introduction to the Access to Information Act</A></H2><P>The <I>Access
to Information Act</I> gives Canadian citizens as well as people and
corporations present in Canada the right to have access to information
in federal government records. The Act ensures that you can ask for
information and, if it is not exempt or excluded, the federal government
must let you see it or give you a copy.</P><P>For guidance on access to
information of a personal nature, please see item no. 3 below,
<a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/ise0001.html#introprivacy">Introdu
ction to the <I>Privacy Act</I>.</A></P><P> Because much of the information
the Canadian government has in its files is accessible, you may be able
to find what you want without making a formal written request under the
Act.  The <STRONG><a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/ise2001.html"
> Guide to Sources of Federal Government Information</A></STRONG> will
help you find the telephone numbers of the people who can give you
information on the government's programs and activities.
</P><H3>Using the <I>Access to Information Act</I></H3><P> You always
have the right to apply formally for information under the
<I>Access to Information Act.</I> However, some information may be
exempt or excluded under the Act.</P><P><STRONG>Exemptions:</STRONG>
Exemptions protect certain kinds of information that could cause harm if
released. For example, some information on national security, law
enforcement or trade secrets falls into this category.
</P><P><STRONG>Exclusions:</STRONG>  The Act does not apply to
information that is already available publicly, such as publications or
material in libraries and museums. Cabinet documents are also excluded.
Furthermore, the Act cannot give you access to records that are not
controlled by the federal government, such as those maintained by
provincial or municipal governments or by private organizations like
banks and credit bureaus.
</P><P><STRONG>An Access coordinator's office can help:</STRONG>  Each
federal government department or agency has an Access Coordinator whose
office can help you identify the records you wish to see.
</P><H3>How to apply
</H3><P>Once you have decided to make a formal request under the Act,
there are certain simple procedures to follow.  Please see item no. 4 -
<A>Requesting information under the Acts</A> for further information.
</P><P><STRONG>Turnaround time:</STRONG>  Government departments must
acknowledge your request within 30 days.  However, in special cases,
they may need more time to process your request.
</P><P><STRONG>Reading rooms:</STRONG>  For your convenience, all
federal government departments and agencies have a room set aside where
you can examine the records you requested.
</P><H3>The Information Commissioner</H3>
<P>The Information Commissioner investigates formal complaints
from members of the public arising from the <I>Access to Information
Act.</I> The Commissioner is located at: </P><PRE><STRONG>
     Tower B, Place de Ville
     3rd Floor, 112 Kent Street
     Ottawa, Ontario
     Tel.: 995-2410 (Ottawa-Hull)
     1-800-267-0441 (national toll free)</STRONG>

</PRE><P>For more information about the <I>Access to Information Act</I>
you may contact:       </P><PRE><STRONG>
     Communications and Coordination Directorate
     Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat
     Tel.: (613) 957-2400</STRONG>

</PRE><H2><a name="introprivacy">3. Introduction to the <I>Privacy
Act</I>
</A></H2><P>In its day-to-day operations, federal government
departments and agencies collect personal information from almost all
Canadians.  The <I>Privacy Act</I> gives Canadian citizens and people
present in Canada the right to have access to information that is held
about them by the federal government. It also protects against
unauthorized disclosure of personal information. In addition, it
strictly controls how the government will collect, use, store, disclose
and dispose of any personal information.
</P><P>For guidance on access to information that is not of a personal
nature, please see item no. 2 - <a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/ise0001.html#introaccess">Introduc
tion to the <I>Access to Information Act.</I></A>
</P><H3>Using the <I>Privacy Act</I>
</H3><P><STRONG>Types of personal information held:</STRONG>   Some of
the programs and operations of the government use personal information
about individuals, such as income tax at Revenue Canada, pension and
family allowance payments at Health Canada and the unemployment
insurance program at Human Resources Development Canada.
</P><P>There is some personal information the federal government may
not release under the <I>Privacy Act,</I> much of which relates to
other people, national security or law enforcement.
</P><P><STRONG>How to apply:</STRONG>  When you have decided to make a
formal request under the <I>Privacy Act</I>, there are certain
procedures to follow. Please see item no. 4 - <a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/ise0001.html#requesting">Requesting information under the Acts</A> for details.
</P><P><STRONG>To change the information:</STRONG>  If you believe the
information on file is untrue or misleading, you can ask to have it
corrected. Even if the department or agency does not agree to change
this  information, it must make a note that you have asked for the
change and attach it to the file.
</P><P><STRONG>Safeguarding personal information</STRONG>:  The
protection of personal information is an important part of the <I>Privacy
Act.</I> The Act states how and when the government can collect, store
and dispose of personal information. It also covers specifically why and
how the information can be used or given out, as well as who can use or
receive it.
</P><P><STRONG>Giving out information:</STRONG>  The government can
only disclose your information to someone else with your consent or when
one or more of the criteria in the <I>Privacy Act</I> are met, such as
to comply with a subpoena.
</P><P><STRONG>Turnaround time:</STRONG>  Under the law, the
information you ask for should be provided within 30 days after
receiving the request. If a time extension is required, you will be
notified within the first 30 days and told why up to another 30 days may
be needed.
</P><H3>The Privacy Commissioner can help
</H3><P>The Privacy Commissioner is a representative of the people who
can help if you are dissatisfied with the results of your formal
application. If the Privacy Commissioner recommends that you be given
access and the department or agency still refuses, an appeal may be made
to the Federal Court.
</P><P>You can write or call the Privacy Commissioner's office at:</P><PRE>
<STRONG>
     Place de Ville, Tower B
     112 Kent Street, 3rd Floor
     Ottawa, Ontario
     K1A 1H3
     Telephone: 995-2410 in Ottawa-Hull
     1-800-267-0441 (national toll free number)</STRONG>


</PRE><P>To obtain a brochure on the <I>Access to Information Act</I>
or the
<I>Privacy Act,</I> please contact: </P><PRE><STRONG>

     Distribution Centre
     Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat
     Ottawa, Ontario
     K1A 0R5
     Tel.: (613) 995-2855</STRONG>

</PRE><P>For more information about the <I>Privacy Act</I> you may
contact:       </P><PRE><STRONG>
     Communications and Coordination Directorate
     Treasury Board of Canada Secretariat
     Telephone: (613) 957-2400</STRONG>


</PRE><H2><a name="requesting">4. Requesting Information Under the
Acts
</A></H2><P>The easiest way to request information about the programs
and activities of the federal government is to find out, with the help
of <STRONG>Info Source,</STRONG> which department or agency has the
information you are seeking, and to request it informally by calling the
person in the relevant program area.  The <a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/ise2001.html"
>Guide to Sources of Federal Government Information</A> will help you
find the telephone numbers of the people who can give you information.
</P><H3>Requests made under the <I>Access to Information Act:</I></H3><P>
If you decide to make a formal request under the <I>Access to
Information Act,</I> please follow this procedure:
</P><OL>
<LI>Decide which department or agency is most likely to have the
information you want.  If you require assistance, consult the <STRONG>Info
Source</STRONG> publications or database, where you will find a
description of each institution's program records.  You may also contact
the institution's Access to Information Coordinator.</LI>
<LI>Send either a signed letter saying you are requesting information
under the <I>Access to Information Act</I> or a completed Access to
Information Request form to the federal department or agency you have
selected.  Please write clearly your name, address, telephone number and
a description of the information you are seeking.</LI>
<LI>Include an application fee of $5 for each request. Additional costs
may be charged. You will be notified in advance of additional costs and
you may be asked to make a deposit.</LI></OL><P><STRONG>Turnaround
time:</STRONG>  Government departments must acknowledge your request
within 30 days.  However, in special cases, they may need more time to
process your request.</P><P><STRONG>Reading rooms:</STRONG>  For your
convenience, all federal government departments and agencies have a room
set aside where you can examine the records you requested.</P><P>Access
to Information forms may be obtained at the locations where the <STRONG>Info
Source</STRONG> publications or database are found.
</P><H3>Requests made under the <I>Privacy Act:</I></H3><P>Information
of a personal nature can only be obtained by making a formal request
under the <I>Privacy Act.</I>  The procedure is as follows:
</P><OL>
<LI>Obtain a Personal Information Request Form from a location
where the <STRONG>Info Source</STRONG> publications or database are
available.
</LI>
<LI>Identify yourself in such a way that the government can verify that
it is you, and not someone else, asking for your information.</LI>
<LI>Describe the information you are seeking and provide any  relevant
details necessary to help the institution find it.     The more precise
the information you provide, the faster your  request can be answered.
If you require assistance, refer to <STRONG>Info Source</STRONG> where
you will find the description of the records of a personal nature the
government holds (called Personal Information Banks).  You may also call
the Privacy     Coordinator of the institution which holds the
information you are seeking.</LI>
<LI>Send the form to the Privacy Coordinator of the appropriate
department or agency.  You will find the address in <STRONG>Info
Source</STRONG>.

</LI>
<LI>There is no charge to apply for information under the <I>Privacy
Act.</I></LI></OL><P>When you receive an answer to your request, review
the information to determine whether you wish to make a further request
under the Act.  You also have the right to complain to the Privacy
Commissioner should you believe that you have been denied any of your
rights under the Act.  Please see item no. 3, <a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/ise0001.html#introprivacy">Introdu
ction to the
<I>Privacy Act</I></A> for further details.</P><HR><P><a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/tocenglish.html"><IMG
SRC="http://www.qlsys.ca/TBS/Info_Source/images/petite.gif"></A>
Return to <STRONG>Info Source</STRONG> Main Menu</P>




