<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>LII</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<!-- Any HTML can be put in here for the header -->
<a href="http://www.mcbinch.com/"><img BORDER=1 src="/Link4.gif"></a>
<BR>

<H4>A Hypertext Publication<BR>
of <a href=http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.law.cornell.edu/lii.table.html><img src="http://www.law.cornell.edu:80/icons/yalogo.gif" alt="LII - legal information institute - cornell law school"></A></H4>
<a name=Beginning><H2>The Legal Information Institute-What Is It and Why Is It?</H2></A>
<a href=#authors><H3>Thomas R. Bruce and Peter W. Martin</H3></A>
<I>From the <B>Cornell Law Forum</B>, March 1994, pp. 3-6</I><P>
When the <I>Cornell Law Quarterly, </I>now the <I>Cornell Law Review,</I> was launched nearly 
eighty years ago, Dean Edwin Woodruff expressed the hope that the publication would connect the "work 
and interests of the law school,-- indeed all the "resources" of the school, with members of the profession 
throughout the country. He also wrote of his conviction that the journal would have "pedagogical value 
within the college itself" and by fostering "intelligent discussion and investigation" would aid in "the 
solution of legal problems."<P>
Less than two years ago, pursuing remarkably similar aims, the two of us founded a new venture at the 
law school called the Legal Information Institute. Like the school's journals (including this one) and 
numerous other established activities, the institute seeks to connect the full resources of the school with 
the legal profession, with other law schools, with the world. What distinguishes the LII is the technology 
of that connection; all its publications are electronic. The LII's two primary activities-the distribution of 
course supplements on disk in a hypertext format and the dissemination of legal information via the 
Internet-have led to a variety of related computer-based initiatives.<P>
Dean Woodruff's introduction of the <I>Cornell Law Quarterly</I> assumed his readers understood 
what a law school journal was, and it undertook to explain why the publication of yet another one (even in 
1915, law journals seemed numerous) was not simply wasteful indulgence. Since Cornell's new institute 
is, by contrast, the first of its kind, our introduction of it carries the quite different burden of explaining 
exactly what the LII has set out to do and why.<P>
With generous start-up support from the National Center for Automated Information Research and Mead 
Data Central, and important cooperation from Lawyers Cooperative Publishing and the Folio Corporation, 
we set to work exploring how computer-based information technology might enable the school both to 
pursue long-standing goals more effectively and to venture in new and exciting directions. Our aim was at 
once experimental and applied. It was experimental in the sense that we saw the institute as a vehicle for 
investigating new possibilities, stretching the technology and general understanding of what it can do in 
the field of law. It was applied in that we envisioned the initiatives not as cloistered laboratory 
experiments but as an open-ended series of new services and educational materials designed to be valuable 
to law students, law teachers, members of the profession, and others with an interest in law and legal 
institutions.<P>
<a name=table><B>Overview:</B></A>
<UL><LI><a href ="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.law.cornell.edu:80/lii/lii.disk.html">LII -- Electronic Publisher of Course Materials</A>
<LI><a href ="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.law.cornell.edu:80/lii/lii.internet.html">LII -- Publisher on the Internet</A>
<LI><a href ="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.law.cornell.edu:80/lii/lii.cello.html">Cello -- An Internet Browser</A>
<LI><a href ="http://www.mcbinch.com/cgi-bin/mcbinch/nph-mcb?url=http://www.law.cornell.edu:80/lii/lii.impact.html">LII -- Impact at Cornell</A>
</UL>
<HR>
<a name=authors>Thomas R. Bruce and Peter W. Martin</A> are codirectors of the Legal Information 
Institute. Bruce is a research associate and the former director of educational technologies at the Cornell 
Law School. Martin is the Jane M. G. Foster Professor of Law at the school.
